[[ja:築山古墳 (糸島市)]]
{{Infobox Kofun in Japan
| Name = Tsukiyama Kofun
| Location = {{ill|Fukuoka Prefecture|ja|福岡県}}{{ill|Itoshima|ja|糸島市}} Mikumo Aza Teraguchi
| Coordinates = {{coord|33|32|19.62|N|130|14|41.34|E|region:JP-40_type:landmark|display=inline}}
| Shape = {{ill|Keyhole-shaped tumulus|ja|前方後円墳}}
| Size = Mound length 60 {{ill|meters|ja|メートル}}<br>Height 8m
| Construction Period = Around the end of the {{ill|4th century|ja|4世紀}}
| Person Buried = Unknown
| Historic Site Designation = 
| Excavated Items = {{ill|Pottery|ja|土器}}, {{ill|Haniwa|ja|埴輪}}
| Image = [[File:Tsukiyama Kohun.jpg|280px|Tsukiyama Kofun]]
}}

'''Tsukiyama Kofun''' (築山古墳) is a {{ill|kofun|ja|古墳}} located in {{ill|Mikumo|ja|三雲}}, {{ill|Itoshima|ja|糸島市}}, {{ill|Fukuoka Prefecture|ja|福岡県}}. It is a {{ill|keyhole-shaped tumulus|ja|前方後円墳}}, estimated to have been constructed in the middle of the {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代}}. Although the mound has been significantly flattened, it is believed to have originally had a total length of 60 {{ill|meters|ja|メートル}} with stone coverings (*fukiishi*) applied to its slopes. 

The front section is approximately 15 meters long, while the rear circular section has a diameter of about 49 meters and a height of roughly 8 meters. A {{ill|shield-shaped moat|ja|盾形の周濠}} surrounds the mound, and when including the moat, the total length reaches around 105 meters. Atop the mound, there is a hall enshrining the {{ill|Eleven-faced Kannon|ja|十一面観音}}.

Approximately 100 meters to the north lies the {{ill|Hayama Kofun|ja|端山古墳}} (前方後円墳), estimated to have a total length of 80 meters, constructed in the early {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代}}.

These tumuli are located about 200 meters northeast of {{ill|Saiseki Shrine|ja|細石神社}}, with the {{ill|Hirabaru Site|ja|平原遺跡}} approximately 1 kilometer to the northwest. The area is considered a key region of the ancient {{ill|Itokoku|ja|伊都国}}, as described in the {{ill|Records of Wei|ja|魏志倭人伝}}.

The individuals buried in the tumulus are thought to have been powerful local chieftains closely connected to the {{ill|Yamato polity|ja|大和政権}}, ruling this area in place of the Itokoku kings.<ref>Itoshima City Board of Education</ref> Neither the Tsukiyama Kofun nor the Hayama Kofun has undergone archaeological excavation of their burial facilities.

