'''Tsukiyama Kofun''' (築山古墳) is a {{ill|kofun|ja|古墳|1=Kofun|12=draft|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Mikumo|ja|三雲|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Itoshima|ja|糸島市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Fukuoka Prefecture|ja|福岡県|12=draft|12=draft}}. It is a {{ill|keyhole-shaped tumulus|ja|前方後円墳|1=Zenpokoenfun|12=draft|12=draft}}, estimated to have been constructed in the middle of the {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|12=draft|12=draft}}. Although the mound has been significantly flattened, it is believed to have originally had a total length of 60 {{ill|meters|ja|メートル|12=draft|12=draft}} with stone coverings (*fukiishi*) applied to its slopes. 

The front section is approximately 15 meters long, while the rear circular section has a diameter of about 49 meters and a height of roughly 8 meters. A {{ill|shield-shaped moat|ja|盾形の周濠|12=draft|12=draft}} surrounds the mound, and when including the moat, the total length reaches around 105 meters. Atop the mound, there is a hall enshrining the {{ill|Ekādaśamukha|lt=Eleven-faced Kannon|ja|十一面観音|12=draft|12=draft}}.

Approximately 100 meters to the north lies the {{ill|Hayama Kofun|ja|端山古墳|12=draft|12=draft}} (前方後円墳), estimated to have a total length of 80 meters, constructed in the early {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|12=draft|12=draft}}.

These tumuli are located about 200 meters northeast of {{ill|Saiseki Shrine|ja|細石神社|12=draft|12=draft}}, with the {{ill|Hirabaru Site|ja|平原遺跡|12=draft|12=draft}} approximately 1 kilometer to the northwest. The area is considered a key region of the ancient {{ill|Itokoku|ja|伊都国|1=Itokoku|12=draft|12=draft}}, as described in the {{ill|Records of Wei|ja|魏志倭人伝|12=draft|12=draft}}.

The individuals buried in the tumulus are thought to have been powerful local chieftains closely connected to the {{ill|Yamato polity|ja|大和政権|1=Yamato Kingship|12=draft|12=draft}}, ruling this area in place of the Itokoku kings.<ref>Itoshima City Board of Education</ref> Neither the Tsukiyama Kofun nor the Hayama Kofun has undergone archaeological excavation of their burial facilities.

